title: Java API for onnxruntime
body:
**Description**:
This pull request provides a Java 8 API using JNI. It has unit tests ported from the v0.5.0 release of the C# API, I'll work on porting the new tests from the master branch over the next few weeks. I assume there will be some design & naming discussion on this PR so we can have that while I work on the unit tests.

Currently it builds using a separate gradle project which I've tested on Mac & Linux. The build process involves running `gradle clean build -x test; gradle build` as the combination of a JNI and Java project in Gradle 5 isn't properly supported. I could do with some help integrating it into the CMake build system, but I've not used CMake much before. Integrating it into CMake will make it simpler to put in the appropriate provider compilation flags and fix the oddities in the build (as CMake has all the information necessary).

title: Fix Conv+BN fusion to check that BN does not have optional outputs
body:
**Description**: 
The Conv+BN fusion is missing a check that the BN node does not have optional outputs. If it does, it cannot be fused with the Conv node.

Add the necessary checks.
Trim the output defs in case there are any optional outputs (already checked they don't exist so known to be unused) before finalizing fusion as we copy those to the Conv node to maintain the output names.

Add unit tests for both cases.

**Motivation and Context**
Converter nightly builds fail due to it invalidly fusing a BN node with 4 optional outputs.

title: Jeffbloo/fix dml rnn failures
body:
**Description**: 
The DML EP maintain maps between raw ORT KernelDef pointers and the functors used to create its own nodes within DML graph partitions.  This way, it can always let ORT manage resolving registrations, and have more shared code paths.

This was always inherently fragile, because it assumes the lifetime of KernelDefs exceeds that of the DML EP.  There's now a case where this isnt true.  A separate issue of overlapping DML kernel registrations can result in map entries which key off a pointer that's freed.  This leads to problems for operators which are not expected to have entries in this map (RNN, GRU, LSTM, and ConstantOfShape), if they share an address with that freed pointer.

While addressing the underlying fragility will be nice, this is a scoped fix through better error checking.

**Motivation and Context**
This is believed to have caused sporadic failures with RNN models.  Some of the affected backend test cases were previously disabled, then the DML build was disabled after additional failures were encountered.

title: ReduceMin/ReduceMax do not reduce axes on Cuda provider
body:
**Describe the bug**
When using the Reduce operators (e.g. ReduceMin) with no axes sepcified, and keep_dims==0, the dimensions of the input tensor are not reduced when running via the Cuda provider.  If the exact same Onnx model is used with the CPU provider, the axes are reduced as expected.

**Urgency**
A workaround is possible: instead of 
`m = data.min()`
you can write
`m, _ = data.view(-1).min(dim = 0, keepdim = True)`

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution: Windows 7 x64
- ONNX Runtime installed from: NuGet (C#)
- ONNX Runtime version: 0.5.0, 0.5.1
- Python version: 3.7
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): 2019 (16.3.1)
- CUDA/cuDNN version: 10.0
- GPU model and memory: RTX 2080 Ti

**To Reproduce**
* Create a pytorch model that uses the .min() operator on a tensor with more than one dimension
`data = torch.randn(2, 2)
data_min = data.min()`
* Export the model to onnx, import in OnnxRuntime for C#
* Run the model via CPU e.g.
`new InferenceSession(pathToOnnxFile, SessionOptions.Default);`
* Check the output is a single scalar tensor.
* Run the model via GPU e.g.
`new InferenceSession(pathToOnnxFile, SessionOptions.MakeSessionOptionWithCudaProvider());`
* The output has the same dimensions as the input

**Expected behavior**
The results should be the same for both providers; and the number of dimensions should be reduced.

**Additional context**
I'm not a CUDA programmer, but looking at the code in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/90858b732a1d27657fc1424c91ccbfdf46082437/onnxruntime/core/providers/cuda/reduction/reduction_ops.cc#L91 it seems the reduced dimensions are correctly calculated from *output_dims* and stored in *squeezed_output_dims*, but then later, these reduced dimensions are ignored when creating the output tensor https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/90858b732a1d27657fc1424c91ccbfdf46082437/onnxruntime/core/providers/cuda/reduction/reduction_ops.cc#L109

title: resize: clear cache when moving to next channel
body:
**Description**: For cubic interpolation we use a 4x4 grid. There is a potential to cache the results during interpolation since there is an overlap when moving from position to position. However this cache is only valid for 2D .i.e H*W ... and it needs to be cleared when moving to the next channel. This PR clears the cache when moving to next channel. 

**Motivation and Context**
- Fixes a bug when running cubic interpolation in case of multi channel inputs

title: Improve error message from shape inference

labels.name: type:enhancement
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

body:
**Describe the bug**

Currently I get this error in ORT:

> Fail: [ONNXRuntimeError] : 1 : FAIL : Load model from /mnt/output/gr/Models_Classify/model.onnx failed:[ShapeInferenceError] Can't merge shape info. Both source and target dimension have values but they differ. Source=96 Target=64 Dimension=1

But there is no information as which node is the culprit.

This is another error that knowing node name could help

> [ShapeInferenceError] Attribute pads has incorrect size


**Urgency**
Need this for converting a CNTK model

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Ubuntu 16.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): master
- ONNX Runtime version: master
- Python version: 3.6

**To Reproduce**
The original CNTK model after conversion hits [this issue](https://github.com/microsoft/CNTK/issues/3671) that is referenced [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/1133). The input dimension is `Sequencex1x3x244x244`.

I use this to remove `Sequence` and let shape inference be done in ORT:

```python
import onnx

onnx_model = onnx.load(onnxfile)
graph = onnx_model.graph

for tensor_info in [graph.input, graph.output]:
    for value_info in tensor_info:
        dim = value_info.type.tensor_type.shape.dim
        if not len(dim):
            continue
        val = getattr(dim[0], "dim_param", None)
        if val == 'Sequence':
            dim.remove(dim[0])

while len(graph.value_info):
    graph.value_info.remove(graph.value_info[0])

onnx.save(onnx_model, onnxfile)
```

Only now I get the new error about shape inference

**Expected behavior**
I know the [error message is from ONNX](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/issues/2421) but better error message could be displayed by ORT that has more information, about node name for example

**Additional context**
No point in opening issue for CNTK onnx exporter, so need to work around the bug

title: Slice test for reverse
body:
**Describe the bug**
ONNX spec inconsistency in Slice op for opset 10.

In Slice_op.test.cc, there are some tests for [reversing](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/test/providers/cpu/tensor/slice_op.test.cc#L420-L433). In the test, INT_MAX is used for end, while -1 for start, with -1 for step. The test verifies the output to reversing the specified axis. However, this behavior is not clarified in ONNX spec for [Slice](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#Slice). Moreover, when changing the test to use [start/end/axes/step as initializer](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/test/providers/cpu/tensor/slice_op.test.cc#L38-L43) by using AddInput(..., true), the test crashes in ONNX shape inference, as the computed shape is 0 from ONNX shape inference. When start/end/axes/step are not initializers, ONNX shape inference bypasses the Slice node, so this bug is not triggered.

**Urgency**

If there are models relying on this behavior, it will not work if the input for start/end/axes/step changed from dynamic input to initializers. This may also cause confusion to other providers implementing Slice op.

**System information**
Any

**To Reproduce**
Change slice_op.test.cc to use [start/end/axes/step as initializer](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/test/providers/cpu/tensor/slice_op.test.cc#L38-L43) by using AddInput(..., true)

**Expected behavior**
The Slice for Reversing tests should pass with proper shape inference fixes in ONNX, and doc clarifications. Otherwise, those tests should be removed to avoid inconsistency with spec.

**Screenshots**
N/A

**Additional context**
N/A

**Describe the bug**
When instantiating an InferenceSession using the YoloV3 model obtained from the ONNX Model Zoo ([source](https://github.com/onnx/models/tree/master/vision/object_detection_segmentation/yolov3)), and using a CUDA provider, I obtain the following warnings:

> 2019-11-04 08:51:18.0946732 [W:onnxruntime:CSharpOnnxRuntime, cuda_execution_provider.cc:1112 onnxruntime::CUDAExecutionProvider::GetCapability] CUDA kernel not supported. Fallback to CPU execution provider for Op type: Conv node name: conv2d_2_0                                                                                                                  2019-11-04 08:51:18.0949392 [W:onnxruntime:CSharpOnnxRuntime, cuda_execution_provider.cc:1112 onnxruntime::CUDAExecutionProvider::GetCapability] CUDA kernel not supported. Fallback to CPU execution provider for Op type: Conv node name: conv2d_5_0                                                                                                                  2019-11-04 08:51:18.0959455 [W:onnxruntime:CSharpOnnxRuntime, cuda_execution_provider.cc:1112 onnxruntime::CUDAExecutionProvider::GetCapability] CUDA kernel not supported. Fallback to CPU execution provider for Op type: Conv node name: conv2d_10_0                                                                                                                 2019-11-04 08:51:18.0962491 [W:onnxruntime:CSharpOnnxRuntime, cuda_execution_provider.cc:1112 onnxruntime::CUDAExecutionProvider::GetCapability] CUDA kernel not supported. Fallback to CPU execution provider for Op type: Conv node name: conv2d_27_0                                                                                                                 2019-11-04 08:51:18.0965944 [W:onnxruntime:CSharpOnnxRuntime, cuda_execution_provider.cc:1112 onnxruntime::CUDAExecutionProvider::GetCapability] CUDA kernel not supported. Fallback to CPU execution provider for Op type: Conv node name: conv2d_44_0


**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows 10
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): Latest NuGet release (1.0.0)
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.0.0
- Python version: -
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): Visual Studio 2019 16.3.6
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): -
- CUDA/cuDNN version: CUDA=10.0, cuDNN=7.6 for 10.0
- GPU model and memory: Nvidia GeForce 940MX 2GB

**To Reproduce**
```C#
int gpuIndex = 0;
var modelPath = "yolov3.onnx";
var session = new InferenceSession(modelPath, SessionOptions.MakeSessionOptionWithCudaProvider(gpuIndex));
```


**Expected behavior**
I do not expect the runtime to fallback to CPU for these convolutional layers.

**Screenshots**
Screenshots of Task Manager showing high CPU utilization and some GPU utilization during repeated inference on the same data. This along with the warnings makes me think that CUDA is used for some layers in the network, but not for the onex listed in the warning messages.
![CpuUtil](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/23279510/68107378-f81a9100-fee4-11e9-881b-2801dc39cbc1.PNG)
![GpuUtil](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/23279510/68107452-3d3ec300-fee5-11e9-94d2-bd382675f586.PNG)


**Additional context**
On inspection of the YoloV3 Model in [Netron](https://lutzroeder.github.io/netron/), I can see no real difference between the conv2d layers for which CUDA support fails and the conv2d layers for which it succeeds, other than the property AUTO_PAD being NOTSET for the failing layers (and they have a property "pads" specifying the padding). Furthermore, the failing layers end with an additional "_0" in the names.
